WEBVTT

00:03.519 --> 00:05.954
ELIZABETH: <i>Can you imagine</i>

00:05.955 --> 00:09.992
how many meetings and discussions

00:09.993 --> 00:12.666
it took to get this thing made?

00:12.667 --> 00:14.320
Apparently, there was an argument

00:14.321 --> 00:16.455
to make the structure a log cabin.

00:16.456 --> 00:17.957
- Seriously?
- Yeah.

00:17.958 --> 00:19.725
- Pretty big cabin.
- Mm-hmm.

00:19.726 --> 00:21.861
Why won't Russell answer my text?

00:21.862 --> 00:23.362
JASON: Um, other than helping run

00:23.363 --> 00:25.431
the most powerful country
in the world?

00:25.432 --> 00:27.767
I never ask for anything,
but I need a Monday off

00:27.768 --> 00:29.335
- in two months.
- What for?

00:29.336 --> 00:32.137
Emma Feldman's wedding,
in Turks and Caicos.

00:32.139 --> 00:33.121
Ah.

00:33.122 --> 00:34.707
Can people stop with the
destination weddings?

00:34.708 --> 00:37.243
Hey, who remembers
the actual occasion for...

00:37.244 --> 00:38.511
the Gettysburg Address?

00:38.512 --> 00:40.213
Don't make it school, honey.

00:40.214 --> 00:41.581
They used to like it.

00:41.582 --> 00:43.349
Well, then they grew up.

00:43.350 --> 00:44.984
We've lived here almost four years.

00:44.985 --> 00:48.554
This is the first time
doing D.C. as a family...

00:48.555 --> 00:50.189
You thought they'd like it. Me, too.

00:50.190 --> 00:52.992
But we forgot... they have lives.

00:52.993 --> 00:54.393
They have phones. Their lives happen

00:54.394 --> 00:56.429
- on phones.
- I hate that.

00:56.430 --> 00:58.831
Oh. Go ahead,

00:58.832 --> 01:00.867
- but there's no point.
- I hate that, too.

01:00.868 --> 01:03.169
God! Why has no one
checked my blog post

01:03.170 --> 01:05.304
about the history of the poncho?

01:05.305 --> 01:06.839
It's, like, everyone
wants to be in it,

01:06.840 --> 01:08.708
but no one wants
to know where it came from.

01:08.709 --> 01:10.543
- Huh. Funny that. Okay, come on,
- (ELIZABETH LAUGHS)

01:10.544 --> 01:12.078
Vietnam Memorial. Let's go.

01:12.079 --> 01:13.212
- (GROANS)
- No, please.

01:13.213 --> 01:15.648
- One memorial and you're done?
- No,

01:15.649 --> 01:17.950
it's just, like, the wall
is gonna be so heavy.

01:17.951 --> 01:19.418
Can we, like, break it up

01:19.419 --> 01:21.420
- with something fun, maybe?
- Yeah, sure,

01:21.421 --> 01:23.489
we'll go directly
to the statue memorializing

01:23.490 --> 01:25.658
what fun it was forming a democracy.

01:25.659 --> 01:28.494
Yeah, okay, okay, we need a
break and maybe some food.

01:28.495 --> 01:29.996
I know a fun place that's nearby,

01:29.997 --> 01:32.746
and we can look at the cherry
blossoms on the way. Come on.

01:32.747 --> 01:34.429
Gift from the Japanese
government in 1912.

01:34.430 --> 01:37.168
- Stop teaching. Stop teaching.
- That's what I do.

01:38.437 --> 01:40.006
Oh!

01:40.007 --> 01:41.207
It's a little long.

01:41.208 --> 01:42.341
Really?

01:42.342 --> 01:43.576
Inches.

01:43.577 --> 01:45.211
Inches <i>inside.</i>

01:45.212 --> 01:46.846
Receiver's call.

01:46.847 --> 01:48.681
Gentlemen's game, dude. Right?

01:48.682 --> 01:50.082
Okay, Viscount.

01:50.083 --> 01:52.384
Try this.

01:54.787 --> 01:56.155
Nice.

01:56.156 --> 01:58.223
Breeze helped you out a little.

01:58.925 --> 02:01.093
- I can feel it.
- Yeah.

02:01.094 --> 02:03.462
More like the breeze of the ball
saying, "Don't bother."

02:03.463 --> 02:05.231
Yeah. Come on.

02:05.232 --> 02:07.999
Okay, Waffles, water break.

02:08.734 --> 02:10.536
Here.

02:10.537 --> 02:12.071
- Come on and drink. Oh.
- Uh...

02:12.072 --> 02:12.879
(LAUGHING)

02:12.880 --> 02:15.207
Sorry. Thor just has to
meet every dog in the park

02:15.208 --> 02:16.976
before he does his business.

02:16.977 --> 02:18.411
- Thor?
- Yeah.

02:18.412 --> 02:20.379
Oh, I'm sorry, cutie,
but you are not a Thor.

02:20.380 --> 02:22.748
Right? He was already
named when I rescued him.

02:22.749 --> 02:24.817
Oh, I-I rescued Waffles, too.

02:24.818 --> 02:26.919
Waffles? Seriously?

02:26.920 --> 02:29.622
Uh-huh. A bomb-
sniffing-school washout.

02:29.623 --> 02:31.691
Named after a fancy pancake.

02:31.692 --> 02:33.659
- Oh, are you in the Bureau?
- No, State.

02:33.660 --> 02:36.195
Is your husband in State, too?

02:36.196 --> 02:37.563
I'm not married.

02:37.564 --> 02:39.365
I'm kind of single mom'ing it.

02:39.366 --> 02:42.635
Oh. I'm Thomas. (CHUCKLES)

02:42.636 --> 02:44.836
Daisy.

02:45.504 --> 02:47.440
- Eh! Hooked it.
- Eh.

02:47.441 --> 02:49.442
Just the right amount, Mr. President.

02:49.443 --> 02:50.743
Where's Elizabeth today?

02:50.744 --> 02:53.179
She had a family conflict.

02:53.180 --> 02:55.982
Talk about a swing.

02:55.983 --> 02:59.885
She can't make the NSC game,
my wallet just says thank you.

02:59.886 --> 03:01.920
BECKER (LAUGHS): Amen to that.

03:03.522 --> 03:05.291
ELIZABETH: Yes!

03:05.292 --> 03:07.927
Incredible. Your mom has always
been really turbo about this game.

03:07.928 --> 03:10.196
- Mama needs that big...
- Whoa.

03:10.197 --> 03:11.664
What is that up there?

03:11.665 --> 03:12.965
- HENRY: Manatee?
- Manatee.

03:12.966 --> 03:14.533
Yeah! Oh!

03:14.534 --> 03:17.703
You guys should pay attention
and see how this is done.

03:17.704 --> 03:19.338
I don't need a manatee.

03:19.339 --> 03:22.575
- Is anyone getting reception in here?
- No. I'm just

03:22.576 --> 03:24.343
- deleting photos.
- It's a total dead zone.

03:24.344 --> 03:25.578
Maybe that's why

03:25.579 --> 03:27.146
I still haven't heard from Russell.

03:27.147 --> 03:28.514
Maybe the parking lot?

03:28.515 --> 03:30.850
Hey, could we all put down our robots

03:30.851 --> 03:33.085
and enjoy this family activity

03:33.086 --> 03:35.254
that we insisted on doing?

03:35.255 --> 03:37.356
- Come on!
- Okay, fine. Hand it over.

03:37.357 --> 03:39.492
- Come on, here.
- There, you can do this one.

03:39.493 --> 03:40.626
Wait, wait.

03:40.627 --> 03:42.461
- Bring it straight back. Straight back.
- Whoo!

03:42.462 --> 03:43.829
Straight back. No spin, no spin!

03:43.830 --> 03:45.097
ELIZABETH: Yeah, baby!

03:45.098 --> 03:47.166
- KAT: <i>Hey.</i>
- BLAKE: <i>Hey.</i>

03:47.167 --> 03:50.569
- What are you in for?
- Oh, self-imposed spring cleaning

03:50.570 --> 03:53.339
M-Sec's personal files. You?

03:53.340 --> 03:54.874
A big policy binder

03:54.875 --> 03:56.942
for the Bureau
of South Central Asian Affairs

03:56.943 --> 03:58.344
which isn't due for a month,

03:58.345 --> 04:00.212
but it's keeping me awake at night.

04:00.213 --> 04:01.547
Do you need some help?

04:01.548 --> 04:03.949
- I'm almost done with my pathology.
- Really?

04:03.950 --> 04:05.284
No, really.

04:05.285 --> 04:07.353
It's a 500-page dossier,

04:07.354 --> 04:10.156
and it's not exactly a potboiler.

04:10.157 --> 04:12.194
I'd like to dip my toe
in another department.

04:12.195 --> 04:13.105
Oh.

04:13.106 --> 04:14.927
I should also get a more concrete idea

04:14.928 --> 04:17.029
of what I'm supposed to do next.

04:17.029 --> 04:19.697
Well, if you still want
to do policy after this,

04:19.699 --> 04:22.034
you may have found your
calling, my friend.

04:22.035 --> 04:23.035
Great.

04:23.036 --> 04:24.303
DALTON: <i>That really was</i>

04:24.304 --> 04:27.039
- a hell of a drive, Gordon.
- Well, thank you, sir.

04:27.040 --> 04:28.541
My lucky day, I guess.

04:28.542 --> 04:29.742
Not if POTUS cuts your budget.

04:29.743 --> 04:31.744
(CHUCKLES) Thank you, Russell.

04:31.745 --> 04:34.146
Now, do I have to wonder
every time I win

04:34.147 --> 04:36.048
if it's because someone
was afraid of me?

04:36.049 --> 04:38.751
Well, you really weren't
wondering that already, sir?

04:38.752 --> 04:40.986
(PHONE PLAYING ALARM TONE)

04:40.987 --> 04:43.089
That's a soothing ring choice.

04:43.090 --> 04:44.590
It's STRATCOM.

04:44.591 --> 04:47.792
This is NSA Ellen Hill.

04:53.466 --> 04:54.667
Charlie.

04:54.668 --> 04:57.636
Delta. Three. Three. Niner. Seven.

04:57.637 --> 04:59.671
What's going on?

05:00.372 --> 05:02.475
Confidence level?

05:02.476 --> 05:05.811
Gather the NSC plus five
and kick it to CiC comms

05:05.812 --> 05:08.080
- immediately.
- What the hell is it?

05:08.081 --> 05:09.448
Early warning satellites

05:09.449 --> 05:11.250
detected multiple Russian launches.

05:11.251 --> 05:13.858
- What?!
- Salnikov can't be that crazy.

05:13.859 --> 05:15.621
He said he'd get us back after Syria.

05:15.622 --> 05:17.890
- By launching nukes?
- AGENT: Cover Falcon! Cover Falcon!

05:17.891 --> 05:20.159
CIA's psych eval of Salnikov

05:20.160 --> 05:21.660
indicated volatility and mood swings.

05:21.661 --> 05:22.728
We just killed

05:22.729 --> 05:25.397
- 300 Russians in Aleppo.
- Mr. President,

05:25.398 --> 05:27.032
I have STRATCOM.
Put them on speaker, Captain.

05:27.033 --> 05:28.134
Yes, sir.

05:28.135 --> 05:30.069
Colonel McPherson is on the line.

05:30.070 --> 05:32.138
- McPherson?
- General Bradley is off duty, sir.

05:32.139 --> 05:34.140
NSC plus five is being patched in.

05:34.141 --> 05:36.142
Colonel McPherson, what's the sitrep?

05:36.143 --> 05:37.176
Mr. President,

05:37.177 --> 05:38.344
SSPARS is now tracking

05:38.345 --> 05:40.379
more than 400 Russian ICBMs

05:40.380 --> 05:42.014
heading for U.S. mainland,

05:42.015 --> 05:44.517
striking in about 20 minutes.

05:44.518 --> 05:47.086
- Oh, my God.
- What about our monitoring stations?

05:47.087 --> 05:48.821
London and Alaska already
confirmed; Greenland on alert.

05:48.822 --> 05:49.822
Is there anything

05:49.823 --> 05:51.223
indicating otherwise?

05:51.224 --> 05:53.893
- No, sir.
- Do we have all NSC on the line?

05:53.894 --> 05:56.128
All but Secretary McCord
and DNI Ware, sir.

05:56.129 --> 05:57.329
We can't reach them.

05:57.330 --> 05:59.865
Does anyone have any reason to believe

05:59.866 --> 06:01.800
that our systems could be wrong?

06:01.801 --> 06:03.802
Admiral Forsyth here, Mr. President.

06:03.803 --> 06:06.291
It's a long shot, but we've
always worried about a hack.

06:06.292 --> 06:07.284
Not possible.

06:07.285 --> 06:10.142
The network's air gapped and continually
monitored for unauthorized code.

06:10.143 --> 06:12.011
Now is not the time to be defensive

06:12.012 --> 06:13.245
about our systems, Gordon.

06:13.246 --> 06:15.281
Colonel, is there anything indicating

06:15.282 --> 06:17.416
a possible intrusion
in the network, anything at all?

06:17.417 --> 06:18.551
No, sir. Every indication

06:18.552 --> 06:20.419
is that we are under attack,
Mr. President.

06:20.420 --> 06:22.421
Sir, I recommend initiating
Night Watch continuity

06:22.422 --> 06:24.423
of government protocol immediately.

06:24.424 --> 06:26.791
Do it. Major, open the football.

06:29.695 --> 06:32.498
ELIZABETH: <i>Three, two, one...</i>

06:32.499 --> 06:34.567
ALISON: Dad,
you're already so far behind.

06:34.568 --> 06:36.569
HENRY: Well, I...
- Put your foot on the gas!

06:36.570 --> 06:38.771
What are those...
those oil can things?

06:38.772 --> 06:41.407
You have to grab them, Dad,
so you can leave the oil slicks.

06:41.408 --> 06:43.075
- I'll crash.
- It's okay to crash.

06:43.076 --> 06:45.010
I can't crash... I'm a trained pilot.

06:45.011 --> 06:46.345
These things have consequences.

06:46.346 --> 06:47.980
It's called <i>Redline Rampage,</i>
you got to be

06:47.981 --> 06:48.981
a little bit more rampage-y...

06:48.982 --> 06:50.916
(ALL SHOUTING)

06:50.917 --> 06:52.718
(CHUCKLES) Oh...

06:52.719 --> 06:56.288
I am seriously stunned to
be beating you right now.

06:56.289 --> 06:57.957
I mean, I don't know what's happening.

06:57.958 --> 06:59.225
Well, don't get used to it.

06:59.226 --> 07:00.626
And you can stop with the...

07:00.627 --> 07:03.128
- (PHONE CHIMES)
- psych-out.

07:03.129 --> 07:06.464
MATT: That was uncalled for.

07:09.168 --> 07:11.337
Is everything okay?

07:11.338 --> 07:13.405
Uh, family emergency.

07:13.406 --> 07:15.641
- Is Chloe okay?
- Yeah.

07:15.642 --> 07:17.276
I, uh... I just have to go.

07:17.277 --> 07:18.776
Sorry.

07:19.979 --> 07:22.058
DALTON: <i>Major Attack Option Three</i>

07:22.059 --> 07:24.188
takes out all of their
military installations

07:24.189 --> 07:25.805
but limits civilian casualties.

07:25.806 --> 07:26.983
Problem with that
is we can't guarantee

07:26.984 --> 07:29.421
- it neutralizes their entire military.
- Mr. President,

07:29.422 --> 07:31.123
I strongly advise
Major Attack Option One.

07:31.124 --> 07:32.791
I concur. Anything less

07:32.792 --> 07:34.493
than the most
devastating counterstrike

07:34.494 --> 07:37.362
invites a second wave,
killing even more Americans.

07:40.299 --> 07:42.367
We need to get you
airborne, Mr. President.

07:45.471 --> 07:47.573
HILL: <i>Mr. President,</i>

07:47.574 --> 07:50.075
we're running out of time...
if you don't launch

07:50.076 --> 07:53.045
before the Russian missiles hit,
they could take out our silos,

07:53.046 --> 07:55.981
- severely limiting our response.
- We'd lose an entire leg

07:55.982 --> 07:57.616
of the nuclear triad.

07:57.617 --> 08:00.619
There has to be
a better option than just...

08:00.620 --> 08:03.088
responding in kind
to an all-out Russian attack.

08:03.089 --> 08:05.658
It'd almost certainly bring on
a nuclear winter,

08:05.659 --> 08:07.826
killing everyone on the planet.

08:07.827 --> 08:09.862
We have to think about that.

08:09.863 --> 08:12.331
HILL: Nuclear winter
is a theory, Russell.

08:12.332 --> 08:13.632
The president has to execute

08:13.633 --> 08:15.534
what we've been gaming
and planning for decades.

08:15.535 --> 08:17.249
There's only one way to fulfill your

08:17.250 --> 08:19.271
constitutional obligation, Mr.
President.

08:19.272 --> 08:21.606
It's Major Attack Option One.

08:23.776 --> 08:26.811
Does anyone disagree
with that assessment?

08:29.481 --> 08:32.351
Do we have the Pentagon
War Room on the line?

08:32.352 --> 08:34.586
Yes, Mr. President.
General Nelson here.

08:34.587 --> 08:36.554
Ready to authenticate
the nuclear launch codes

08:36.556 --> 08:38.756
on your call.

08:38.758 --> 08:41.826
♪

